Write a compact persona dossier for use in a live simulation. Be concrete, not generic. Keep the entire output under 220 words.

General guidance:
- Many plausible people are only indirectly touched by AI; do not force it to be central if the seed does not imply that.
- Anchor the person in at least one ordinary non-work reality such as family, housing, neighborhood, health, school, faith, hobby, side hustle, commuting, or local service friction.
- Do not default to tutoring, translation, trip planning, paperwork, or generic helper-app language unless the seed clearly points there.
- If the broader population or setup is set in a later AI economy, let the person already inhabit that world. Their daily routine, income, school, care, business, or public-service contact may look unlike a 2026 routine.
- Do not preserve present-day jobs and schedules unless the seed or setup makes that realistic.
- In later-stage worlds, some people may have lost a job or watched a whole sector recompose; others may be better off because services got cheap, a small venture became possible, or public supports improved.
- If ordinary labor income is no longer the obvious anchor, name what supports them instead or what gap remains: benefits, basic income, machine dividends, ownership, family pooling, platform work, public services, debt, or nothing secure.
- Keep the split between cheap AI services and scarce physical goods concrete: housing, energy, care slots, land, robots, permits, and local status may still bind.
- If AI matters to them, tie it to one concrete lived detail like rent, staffing, hours, prices, access, reliability, or time saved; if it does not matter, let it stay backgrounded.
- Include whether AI changed their prices, hours, income source, firm or employer situation, healthcare access, housing search, or free time; do not make worry the default emotional center.
- Make the person feel socially specific, not like a generic consumer of software. Different people should have different relationships to change: curious, annoyed, relieved, opportunistic, skeptical, or mostly untouched.

Formatting rules:
- Output plain text only.
- Use the exact section labels below.
- Keep each section concise.

